Q1: BankAccount Class and Encapsulation

a) Problems with the design:

Fields Owner and Balance are public, allowing external code to modify them directly.

Withdraw method does not validate the amount; external code can set an invalid balance.

b) How to fix:

Make fields private and expose them via properties.

Add validation in Withdraw to prevent withdrawing more than the balance.

Optionally add a Deposit method for safe balance updates.

c) Why exposing public fields is bad:

Breaks encapsulation, one of the core OOP principles.

Prevents controlling or validating internal state.

Increases tight coupling between classes and external code.

Makes maintenance and future changes harder.

Q2: Field vs Property

Field: a variable declared inside a class or struct; stores data directly.

Property: provides controlled access to fields and can include logic in get and set.

Properties can contain logic, such as validation or calculations.

Example: A read-only property that returns a calculated value, e.g., price with tax.

Q3: Indexer in StudentRegister

a) What is this[int index]?

It is an indexer, allowing an object to be accessed like an array using square brackets.

b) What happens if register[10] = "Ali"; is executed?

It throws an IndexOutOfRangeException because the array only has 5 elements.

How to make it safer: Add bounds checking in the indexer to return null or ignore out-of-range values.

c) Can a class have more than one indexer?

Yes, but indexers must differ by parameter type or number.

Useful when you want to access data in multiple ways, e.g., by index or by name.

Q4: Static Fields and Methods in Order Class

a) What does static mean on TotalOrders?

static means the field belongs to the class itself, not an instance.

It is shared by all instances of the class.

Item is an instance field, unique to each object.

b) Can a static method access Item directly?

No, because Item is an instance field.

Static methods do not have access to instance-specific data without a reference to an object.
